init_text:
Is Listening to a Book Just as Good as Reading It?

Do you listen to audiobooks? What are the benefits, in your opinion, of listening instead of reading? Are there advantages to reading that cannot be gained by listening? Which method do you prefer? Why?

---

In my opinion,

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I have no argument with audiobooks, but when it comes to pure enjoyment and pleasure, nothing beats a real book in my hands, feeling the

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: paper, the weight, turning the pages, smelling and feeling the book jacket, seeing my neat handwriting on the inside page of the front cover.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I love to get an interesting or unusual book from a library or an antiquarian store or a friend, and then get to know the book and its

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The smell of an old leather-bound book is a metaphor for the wisdom and beauty locked inside.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: An audiobook is not quite the same experience.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: go to bed with a gadget.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: So I favor real books that I can hold in my hands, and turn the pages lovingly.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: The book itself is part of the experience, and I feel cheated when I listen to an audio-book.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: I feel almost as if someone might "steal the soul" out of the book for me.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You miss out on a lot when you listen rather than go through the book yourself.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: Some of it is simply the physical experience.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You don't enjoy the book in the same way, and you don't form the same attachments.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: You don't write in it, you don't look at the photos or illustrations in it.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And I wonder how much of the story is lost because it is read to you, rather than read by yourself.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: And there's nothing wrong with either one, but neither can take the place of the other.

actions.name: text-insert
actions.text: worth more than any convenience I might ever get from listening to a book.
